truenas-pylibvirt (0.1.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Add nsexec subpackage for entering a running libvirt-LXC container.
    Entry point is `python3 -m truenas_pylibvirt.nsexec`; direct use of
    the C primitives from a multi-threaded daemon is unsafe.
  * Ship a C extension (truenas_pylibvirt.nsexec._native) linked against
    libcap. enter_and_exec switches non-user namespaces, then the user
    namespace, applies bounding-set drops and an explicit
    effective+permitted set, then forks via os.fork(). In the child:
    setresgid/setresuid(0,0,0) re-anchors to in-ns root and
    PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS blocks setuid escalation through the rootfs
    before execv.
  * The launcher migrates itself into the container's unified-hierarchy
    cgroup before fork, so the exec'd shell inherits the container's
    pids/memory/CPU/IO limits and a fork-bomb cannot escape to the host.
  * Namespace fds come from virDomainLxcOpenNamespace (exposed as
    libvirt_lxc.lxcOpenNamespace), avoiding the PID-reuse race against
    opening /proc/<pid>/ns/* directly.
  * ALL_CAPABILITIES is enumerated at import time from libcap, so
    kernel/libcap upgrades pick up new capability names without source
    edits.
  * Export DEFAULT_CONTAINERS_URI and DEFAULT_VMS_URI; DomainManagers
    defaults now reference these constants.
  * Package is architecture-specific (was arch: all); libcap-dev added
    to Build-Depends.

 -- TrueNAS Engineering <dev@truenas.com>  Fri, 24 Apr 2026 10:00:00 -0500

